ACUTE PULM.-RENAL SYNDROME - SAUDI ARABIA (MECCA) (02)
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Acute pulmonary-renal syndrome - Saudi Arabia (Mecca) 20000331220823
[1
Date: 1 Apr 2000
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

I ran this [set of clinical and laboratory findings for the cases of acute
pulmonary-renal syndrome past GIDEON <http://www.cyinfo.com> and came up
with the following.
Further positive AND negative clinical data would be very useful here.
Assuming that both cases are 1) related; 2) acquired in Saudi Arabia (i.e.,
not the Netherlands); and 3) a single infectious disease, the differential
diagnosis should include:
GIDEON Clinical Summary
+ The patient is an adult
+ Severely ill or requires hospitalization
+ Neutrophilia
- Thrombocytopenia
- Hepatic dysfunction
+ Renal dysfunction
+ Case cluster - common source or factor
Begining of exposure: 14 days prior to admission
End of exposure: 4 days prior to admission
Onset of disease: 3 days prior to admission
Diseases Probability:
Legionellosis 73.8%
Septicemia - bacterial 13.5%
Leptospirosis 12.4%
Influenza
Dengue *
Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever **
Typhoid and enteric fever
_Escherichia coli_ diarrhea
Varicella
Malaria ***
Q fever ****
An additional 10 possibilities are given low probability. The Hantaviruses
are in fact clinically compatible, but discounted by GIDEON for lack of
known presence in Saudi Arabia.
Additional notes:
* Dengue was once prevalent. A fatal case of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF)
was reported in Jeddah in 1969 (possibly introduced). 315 cases (suspected
and confirmed) were registered in 1994, including 2 nonfatal cases of DHF
in Jeddah.
** Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever was first reported in Saudi Arabia in
1990 (an outbreak among abattoir workers in Mecca).
- Sporadic cases have been registered in Mecca and elsewhere in the Western
Province, Jeddah and Taif. Serological testing subsequently identified 40
cases (12 fatal) which occurred during 1989 to 1990.
- The local reservoirs are sheep and goats. Ticks present on imported sheep
(particularly from Sudan) have been implicated as the source for infection
in this country.
- Seropositivity rates (1994 to 1996) among imported sheep are 4.1%, goats
3.2%, cattle 0.6% - and 0.8% for persons working with imported livestock.
*** Malaria: _Plasmodium falciparum_ accounts for 80% to 90% of cases.
Chloroquine-resistant _P. falciparum_ IS reported among expatriates (as of
1997, from Pakistan and Sudan). Rare instances of autochthonous
chloroquine-resistant _P. falciparum_ have been reported.
- Disease risk exists year-round in the southwest, except southern Asir,
Jeddah, Mecca, Medina and Taif. 52% of cases are reported from Gizan, 31%
from Asir and 17% from the western region. Transmission is highest in the
south and southwest, during and following the rainy months.
- 15,167 cases were reported in 1982; 17,956 in 1983; 11,091 in 1984;
16,242 in 1985; 12,975 in 1986; 17,650 in 1987 (94% _P. falciparum_); 9,797
in 1988; 6,475 in 1989; 15,666 in 1990. 9,962 cases were reported in 1991;
19,623 in 1992 (of these, approximately 1,300 were imported); 18,380
(320/100,000) in 1993 - 74% of these autochthonous and 85% due to _P.
falciparum_; 10,032 in 1994 (true number estimated at 75,000 with 150
deaths); 18,751 in 1995; 21.007 in 1996; 20,631 in 1997.
- At least 5 Anophelene vectors are active, including _An. stephensi_ in
Eastern Province, and _An. arabiensis_ along Red Sea coast and southwestern
tip. The principal vectors are _Anopheles sergentii_, throughout the
country; _An. pharoensis_ (on the west coast); and _An. pulcherrimus_, _An.
gluviatilis_ and _An. stephensi_ in the northeast.
**** Q-fever: During the late 1960s, 8.4% of persons over 5 years of age
were seropositive (Riyadh).
- The disease is known to occur livestock, and in Arabian oryx (_Oryx
leucoryx_).
--
Stephen Berger, M.D.
e-mail: mberger@post.tau.ac.il
